\begin_layout Standard
We aim to explain how consumer behaviour with respect to effort or investment
 towards their own status changes in response to income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\equiv y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are disposable incomes for the poor and rich consumers (respectively).
 A fundamental assumption that we use for the model is that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fixed in the short-term horizon considered by the consumer (see Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the other condition imposed for the solution).
 The resetting of wealth at a certain period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 that we have considered in the previous version of the model are retained
 in the current formulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by first discussing the degenerate case when players (consumers)
 maximise accumulated assets at an infinite horizon.
 After discussing the futility of positional competition in such a game,
 we consider the case with myopic consumers who are concerned only with
 the asset accumulation at the start of next immediate single-period (see
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The Nash Equilibrium for the formulation and the implications for effects
 of income differences on investments (effort) are then discussed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We maintain that the notion of rich and poor is normative in the model
 and allows a discussion of how parameters controlling promotion and demotion
 probability functions must satisfy a population constraint - which in turn
 reflects the argument that neither promotions nor demotions can continue
 forever in a closed economy (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details of the argument).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main changes that have been made since the previous version of the model
 are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Time Horizons} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - While the previous model fixed the time-horizons when the assets were
 reset in the positional game, the current model adopts a more general approach
 to time-horizons - allowing assets to reset at a general interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\tau$
\end_inset

 rather than at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2$
\end_inset

.
 While the solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 still deals with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

, a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 only amounts to a higher consumer myopia (i.e.
 shorter time-horizon) for positional game in the model.
 The assumptions pertaining to the short-term horizon are detailed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Asset resets as no bequest} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Unlike the previous model which assumed presence of calamitous risk to
 accumulated assets, the current model interprets the long-term horizon
 (or long-term period) 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as the end-of-life for the consumer.
 The reset of assets only represents the fact that the consumer is unable
 to transfer her accumulated assets to the progeny at the end of her life.
 In this no-bequest model, the consumer thus banks upon entirely on the
 game of social positions at the end of her life-cycle.
 The feature also accommodates the dissimilarity between social and economic
 positions - as it is possible for a significant number of players (consumers)
 to achieve a higher socio-economic position in the life-time (i.e.
 the long-term period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) while still failing to transfer their social status to progeny after end-of-li
fe (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BhattacharyaDugar2012CantBuyMeLove"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is discussed in more detail in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Maximisation of Assets accumulation at the start of next period} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Instead of assuming a particular shape of utility function, a closed-form
 solution is discussed with consumers maximising expected assets under risk-neut
ral preferences.
 The martingale requirement for expected asset maximisation is discussed
 and the relevant assumptions are made for optimisation of total assets
 over the short-term horizon (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The effort or investment in the next period is ignored in the short-term
 horizon which the consumer maximises expected assets over.
 In other words, the consumers are assumed to be concerned with the asset
 accumulation only at the start of the immediately next short-term period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Concave Promotion and demotion functions} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The promotion and demotion functions are assumed to have a concave (rather
 than logistic) form in the model (see the second condition in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Long-term population constraint} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - As a normative concern in the model, the population constraint is imposed
 only in the long-term period in the model and has no role for the consumer
 in her short-term asset maximisation.
 This amounts to a constraint on the ratio of promotions to demotions in
 the long-term i.e.
 that on the parameters controlling 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 which are the promotion of demotion functions for poor and rich consumers
 (respectively).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"

\end_inset

Single-Period Assets Maximisation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we discuss Nash Equilibrium for the positional game as well as the
 effects of population constraint on choices of investment (effort) for
 maximisation of assets, it is worthwhile clarifying why the consideration
 of a single-period horizon (i.e.
 current period and the one immediately after) is sufficient for the specificati
on of a positional game.
 Firstly, it is easy to see that the consumer time-horizon must be finite
 in a positional game - which would be inconsequential if the poor and rich
 consumers were already aware of their infinite-horizon assets.
 More particularly, if there exist long-term evaluations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 of the future assets for poor and rich consumers (respectively), then the
 net addition to the assets through the positional game would be zero in
 the long-term equilibrium.
 In this equilibrium, the poor and rich consumers would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})\mathscr{A}_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))\mathscr{A}_{1}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})\mathscr{A}_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))\mathscr{A}_{2}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

- where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are incomes for poorer consumer 1 and richer consumer 2 (respectively),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 represents the time-value of money i.e.
 a discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 are functions for promotion and demotion functions for two respective positions
 (poor and rich) in the game.
 One way this can be achieved is by having 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=\nu_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 when consumer spends all of their income in the effort (investment) and
 their economic position remains stable (due to promotion and demotion probabili
ties implied by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 respectively).
 Any other possible solutions must also maintain that no net value is added
 to the long-term values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and thus positional game is inconsequential for either of the consumers.
 The impracticality of such a result for status competitions does not seem
 at odds for what we observe about them.
 Not only does economic history offer numerous instances of apparently permanent
 (infinite-horizon) income gaps leading to unrest, the idea of maximisation
 of assets at infinite-horizon also leads to well-known paradoxes in consumer
 behaviour studies (e.g.
 St.
 Petersburg paradox - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, while we may consider a general finite multiple-period maximisation,
 we reject it in favour of the single-period assumption since the latter
 circumvents the need to ascertain martingale conditions required for multiple
 periods (using a transform to the risk-neutral probability measure ensuring
 the additivity of assets accumulated over multiple time periods - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harrison1981martingales"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and also allows for more general utility functions (e.g.
 with risk-aversion) where the risk-neutrality condition may be relieved
 (as consumers maximise their utility from assets in a single-period by
 construction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the consideration of a single-period, we now look at the maximisation
 of assets by poor and rich consumers.
 The single-period horizon for the consumer means that the assets maximised
 by the consumer in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 do not include the effort or investment in the next period.
 More specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents the investment (effort) in short-term period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, then the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 does not include 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t+1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,t+1}$
\end_inset

).
 Considering the poorer consumer as consumer 1, the strategy for consumer
 1 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 can be solved by iterations starting with period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and finishing at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The poorer consumer 1 in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 would thus need to maximise the following function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 are the incomes in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 is the effort in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 is the promotion probability in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that at the end-of-life i.e.
 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

, the consumer (a risk-neutral dynast) cannot carry over the accumulated
 assets and must spend everything on the position game - thus letting the
 assets to be augmented in the last period by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer maximises the following function in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{1,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer would add the following value to her assets in the
 last period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

