 In the model with the said population constraint, the life-standards that
 determine the rich or poor status of the consumer - categories which exist
 so long as there is at least one poor or one rich person in the population
 - determine the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 (for a given set of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a life-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and the short-term periods within them (each which are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[1,\tau]$
\end_inset

 that the consumers maximise assets over), the long-term stability of promotions
 and demotions means that the net demotions over a few life-cycles would
 balance out the promotions.
 To consider what the constraint means in terms of the above model, we define
 the ratio of promotions to demotions in every long-term period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
