\begin_layout Standard
Much like intertemporal substitution itself, the population constraint that
 we have argued for in the model is also a normative concept that can be
 specified for a closed economy.
 It may seem at first that the conditions of long-term equilibrium - where
 positions of rich and poor are swapped with no change in their respective
 proportions - do not represent the real-world conditions, the sole motivation
 for population constraint is the existence of rich and poor categories
 in the population.
 The rich and poor only represent the proportional populations in a closed
 economy.
 Thus while demotion being much less likely than promotion (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})>>L(\nu_{2})$
\end_inset

 ) may seem to represent the state of the real-world better - it is easy
 to see that the only way this is possible is when promotions converge to
 zero in the long-term.
 The existence of status competitions implies that a position-less economy
 does not arise in the long-term.
 So long as promotions are plausible for the consumers and are not ruled
 out in the long-term, therefore, one must consider that promotions are
 balanced by demotions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The balance of promotions and demotions in the model is reflected by changes
 in both the income gaps and the life-standards that define poor and rich
 categories in the real-world.
 While the effect of change in income differences on the promotion to demotion
 ratio is evident in the model (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
