\begin_layout Standard
For this discussion, we consider the long-term periods when 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)>1$
\end_inset

 as the promotion regimes and those where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)<1$
\end_inset

 as demotion regimes.
 Immediately after a promotion regime, the population would witness a change
 in composition of rich and poor where there are more rich and less poor.
 More consumers with higher income would mean that the separating line would
 rise in absolute terms (through consumption or saving).
 Not only would the promotions be less because of more rich in the economy,
 but the demotions would be implied solely because many of those who were
 rich would end up becoming poor.
 It is worth emphasising again that such an indirect demotion is a normative
 concern as well.
 Notice also that the population constraint only matters for changes in
 
